This tree is about 5 feet in diameter at the base with four trunks growing from it, each trunk about 18” in diameter! The stories this tree could tell! It's absolutely gorgeous and brings me joy every time I pass it. It's just outside my office window.

This tree is the first thing I see when I step out the front door of my home. In the past, it has been used to hold a bird feeder and during a wind storm, a branch from this tree broke part of the front gutter of my house. Overall, I find this tree a key part of my life living here.

This tree which stands right behind the douglas fir in my front yard is secondary to what I see when I step out the front door. Squirrels and may birds often hang out in it and occasionally, other animals may appear in it too, but the small size of the tree and its branches limits that. Regardless, it has long been a fixture of my yard and will remain a firm staple as such.
37.2 cm circumference

This tree has served a boundary between my property and that of the house next door. It drapes over the roof of my house and over the power line that connects to my house and yet, has never played any roll in cutting off the power supply. Squirrels may end up on the roof by means of this tree. The tree also features a double stem which can be considered an unusual feature for this tree. Overall, while this tree may be easy to go unnoticed due to it being tucked along the side of my house, it still has maintained a strong affiliation for all the years that it has been here.

This tree is secondary to what I see as I leave my house. Birds and squirrels will often inhabit this tree. Sometimes, other animals may be seen in this tree, but its smaller size limits that. This tree also provides acorns for the animals every year and serves as a reminder that this region is garry oak country. Overall, this tree has remained a staple to my house just as much as the douglas fir it sits behind.

This tree which sits tucked along the side of my house serves as a boundary marker between my property and that of the house next door. It drapes over the roof of my house and the power line that connects it, but has never played any part with cutting off power supply. Many needles and cones from this tree gather in the adjacent side gutter of the house due to its close proximity. This particular tree is not a native species to the region and also features a double stem (or "codominant stem") which is an unusual feature for this kind of tree. Overall, this tree may be less noticeable than others, but has long remained an important part for as long as I have been here.
Urban trees are an important part of this environment as they can provide shade and support of wide array of wildlife that thrives in this ecosystem all while we go about our daily activities.

data.text: 115 cm diameter heritage apple tree adjacent to my back yard. It is lovingly pruned and cared for by the neighbours. It had a bumper crop of fruit this fall and many apples dropped on my side of the fence. They lovely for snacking or baking.

Tall, 130cm circumference heritage Bartlett (or similar) pear  tree. This tree is located in the backyard of my rental. The fruit is excellent for pies and is enjoyed by deer who visit our yard. In the spring it produces beautiful blossoms, which I sometimes bring inside as cut flowers.
150 cm circumference blue spruce (Picea pungens). This tree provides habitat for backyard squirrels, raccoons, and songbirds. I admire its silhouette and grey-blue boughs on a daily basis.

I can see this tree from my patio. I often walk past this Garry oak when I'm running errands. Garry oaks are special to me because they remind me of continued lək̓ʷəŋən presence on the land. I find it admirable to witness how nature, such as Garry oaks and their ecosystem, can uplift Indigenous cultural traditions and land management practices!
